title: Redeemer back in Control
subtitle: JOHNSON!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
on-arrival: radical_strength += 1; moderate_strength -= 1; conservative_strength -= 2; liberal_strength -= 2;
tags: event
view-if: year = 1867 and month >= 1
max-visits: 1

= The South Resists Reform

The 1866 elections have delivered a verdict the Radical Republicans refuse to accept. Across the former Confederate states, voters have sent former rebels, Confederate officers, and open opponents of Reconstruction to Washington. Several of the men elected to the House and Senate served in the Confederate army or government. One was the Confederate Vice President himself.

Under Johnson's plan, these men are entitled to their seats. Under any standard of loyalty to the Union, they are not.

The Joint Committee on Reconstruction has been meeting in closed session. These delegations were elected under conditions that cannot be called free under states that have not demonstrated loyalty to the federal government. The committee recommends that Congress exercise its constitutional authority to judge the qualifications of its own members and refuse to seat them.

The choice now falls to us.

- @Refuse: Refuse to seat the Southern delegations in Congress.
- @allow_seating: Allow the Southern members to take their seats.

@Refuse
on-arrival: {!    
    let seatsRemoved = 0;
    let senateSeatsRemoved = 0;
    
    for (let state of Q.southern_states) {
        if (Q.states.indexOf(state) === -1) continue;
        
        let statePop = 0;
        let demVotes = 0;
        let totalVotes = 0;
        
        for (let cls of Q.classes) {
            let pop = Q[state + "_" + cls] || 0;
            let dem = Q[state + "_" + cls + "_dem"] || 0;
            let rep = Q[state + "_" + cls + "_rep"] || 0;
            let other = Q[state + "_" + cls + "_other"] || 0;
            statePop += pop;
            demVotes += pop * dem;
            totalVotes += pop * (dem + rep + other);
        }
        
        let demShare = totalVotes > 0 ? demVotes / totalVotes : 0.6;
        
        let stateHouseSeats = 6;
        let stateDemSeats = Math.round(stateHouseSeats * demShare);
        let stateRepSeats = stateHouseSeats - stateDemSeats;
        
        Q.dem_r = Math.max(0, (Q.dem_r || 0) - stateDemSeats);
        Q.rep_r = Math.max(0, (Q.rep_r || 0) - stateRepSeats);
        seatsRemoved += stateHouseSeats;
        
        let stateDemSenate = Math.round(2 * demShare);
        let stateRepSenate = 2 - stateDemSenate;
        Q.dem_senate_r = Math.max(0, (Q.dem_senate_r || 0) - stateDemSenate);
        Q.rep_senate_r = Math.max(0, (Q.rep_senate_r || 0) - stateRepSenate);
        senateSeatsRemoved += 2;
    }
    
    Q.southern_seats_refused = 1;
    Q.seats_removed = seatsRemoved;
    Q.senate_seats_removed = senateSeatsRemoved;
    
    let totalHouse = Q.rep_r + Q.dem_r + (Q.lib_r || 0) + (Q.other_r || 0);
    let repPct = (Q.rep_r / totalHouse) * 100;
    if (repPct >= 66.7) { Q.house_majority = 3; }
    else if (repPct >= 50) { Q.house_majority = 2; }
    else { Q.house_majority = 0; }
    
    let totalSenate = Q.rep_senate_r + Q.dem_senate_r + (Q.other_senate_r || 0);
    let repSenPct = (Q.rep_senate_r / totalSenate) * 100;
    if (repSenPct >= 66.7) { Q.sen_majority = 3; }
    else if (repSenPct >= 50) { Q.sen_majority = 2; }
    else { Q.sen_majority = 0; }
    
    Q.radical_strength += 5;
    Q.radical_dissent -= 3;
    Q.moderate_strength += 3;
    Q.conservative_dissent += 4;
    Q.dem_relation -= 8;
!}
go-to: Occupation

The Joint Committee moves immediately. The clerk of the House is instructed not to call the names of Southern members when the roll is taken. They are not recognized. They are not given the oath. They stand in the gallery and watch as Congress organizes without them.

The Democrats and President Johnson calls it unconstitutional but we don't give a shit about them.

With [+ seats_removed +] House seats and [+ senate_seats_removed +] Senate seats set aside, the arithmetic of Congress shifts dramatically in our favor.

@allow_seating
on-arrival: {!
    Q.radical_dissent += 8;
    Q.radical_strength -= 3;
    Q.moderate_strength += 2;
    Q.conservative_strength += 3;
    Q.dem_relation += 4;
!}
go-to: Occupation

The Southern delegations are sworn in. Former Confederates take their seats alongside the men who fought to preserve the Union. Radical Republicans are furious. Several walk out of the chamber in protest.

Johnson's allies celebrate. The Democratic caucus, suddenly swelled with Southern members, becomes a far more formidable opposition.

@Occupation

Faced with this reactionary resurgence, Congressional Republicans are now forced to act. Will the federal government take control of Reconstruction and the South itself?

- @full_plan: Enact full military occupation of the south!
- @limited_plan: Enact limited federal oversight
- @Johnson_plan: Maintain Johnson's Reconstruction plan

@full_plan
choose-if: radical_strength >= 35
unavailable-subtitle: [? if radical_strength < 35: Most of our party don't support such radical ideas ?]
on-arrival: {! 

    Q.Radical_plan = 1; 
    Q.Johnson_plan = 0; 
    Q.veto += 1; 
    Q.veto_reason = "Military Reconstruction Act"; 
    Q.occupation = 2; 
    Q.radical_strength += 4; 
    Q.moderate_strength += 2; 
    Q.freedmen_rep += 2; 
    Q.rural_rep -= 1; 
    Q.kkk_strength += 5; 
    Q.kkk_militancy += 0.2;
    for (let state of Q.southern_states) {
        Q[state + "_admitted"] = 0;
    }
!}

Congress passes the **Military Reconstruction Act** of 1867. The South is divided into five military districts under Union command. Confederate officials are removed, and new governments must guarantee Black suffrage.  

Radical Republicans celebrate. But resistance mounts. The Klan stirs in the shadows.

@limited_plan
on-arrival: {!

    Q.Johnson_plan = 0; 
    Q.Moderate_plan = 1; 
    Q.occupation = 1; 
    Q.radical_strength -= 4;  
    Q.moderate_strength += 2; 
    Q.freedmen_rep += 1; 
    Q.rural_rep += 1; 
    Q.conservative_strength += 1; 
    Q.liberal_strength += 1; 
    Q.kkk_strength += 3; 
    Q.kkk_militancy += 0.1;
    for (let state of Q.southern_states) {
        Q[state + "_admitted"] = 0;
    }
!}

Congress compromises on a **moderate Reconstruction plan**: military governors oversee Southern elections, but states retain some autonomy.  

Freedmen gain some protections, but Redeemer influence lingers—and violence persists under the surface.

@Johnson_plan
subtitle: Stay the Course
on-arrival: radical_strength += 5;  radical_dissent += 2; moderate_strength += 1;  moderate_dissent += 1; liberal_dissent +=1

Congress hesitates, and President Johnson’s plan remains in place. Southern states reintegrate quickly, but at a terrible cost.  

Black codes tighten. Freedmen are brutalized. The Radical wing explodes in fury—accusing Johnson of betraying the Union’s victory.
